# CLIMATE INDICATORS | Thematic Section Cryosphere

## Climate Indicators Menu

![Components of the cryosphere](/sites/default/files/inline-images/C3S_indicators_cryosphere_Fig1_0.png)

*Figure 1. Components of the cryosphere. Based on Lemke et al. 2007. Credit: C3S/ECMWF.*  
[HIGH-RESOLUTION IMAGE](/sites/default/files/custom-uploads/Indicators/cryosphere/C3S_indicators_cryosphere_Fig1.pdf)

The term cryosphere derives from the Greek word kryo for cold and encompasses all the parts of the Earth system where water is in solid form, including ice sheets, ice shelves, glaciers, snow cover, permafrost (frozen ground), sea ice, and river and lake ice. The cryosphere exerts an important influence on Earth’s climate, owing to its high surface reflectivity (albedo). This property gives it the ability to reflect a large fraction of solar radiation back into space, and influences how much solar energy is absorbed by land and oceans. Ice on land, in the form of ice sheets and glaciers, plays a further important role in the Earth system through its ability to store vast amounts of water away from the oceans for long periods of time. Any change in the ice volume stored on land, as ice sheets and glaciers grow or shrink, has a direct impact on global mean sea level.

As the climate changes, the cryosphere changes with it and, through feedback processes, these changes have an influence on the climate. For example, the increased melting of snow and ice caused by a warming planet enables more solar energy to be absorbed by land or water, which in turn leads to more warming. This is also known as the snow- or ice-albedo feedback.

There are fundamental differences in the timescales over which the different components of the cryosphere evolve. Due to their large volumes and areas, the continental ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctica undergo changes over timescales of up to millennia, and influence their regional weather and climate. Glaciers, with their much smaller volumes and areas, react to climate drivers at typical timescales of years to centuries. Lake and river ice, at an even smaller size, are good climate indicators at a seasonal timescale. Snow and sea ice are both of small volumes but large areas, with high seasonal variability, and hence interact strongly and rapidly with the atmosphere above, and with the ocean or land surface below. On timescales of years to centuries[[1]](#), permafrost interacts with the global climate through the storage or release of large amounts of methane.

More information on all components of the cryosphere can be found in ‘Further reading’[[2]](#).

## The cryosphere in a changing climate

Observations of some components of the cryosphere have been carried out for a long time. However, to assess global change, vast observational networks, including in situ stations as well as satellites, are needed. This means that reliable global estimates only go back to when such systems were first in place. For example, systematic in situ observations allow for global estimates of glacier change for the last half century, whereas satellite networks have continually improved and expanded to remotely monitor various components of the Earth system: sea ice extent for over four decades, ice sheets for close to three decades and sea ice thickness for the last two decades. Here we present global estimates of change for those components of the cryosphere which are included in the C3S [Climate Indicators](https://climate.copernicus.eu/climate-indicators) and for which data are accessible via the [Climate Data Store](https://cds.climate.copernicus.eu/#!/home). Our assessment highlights the large changes that have already taken place across the cryosphere due to the evolving climate.

Globally, more than 215 000 glaciers – distinct from the Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets – cover an area of about 700 000 km2 with a total volume of about 158 000 km3 of ice[[6]](#). If this ice were to melt, it would cause global sea level to rise by 0.32 ± 0.08 m[[7]](#).

Estimates based on field measurements and satellite observations[[8]](#) show that the global mass loss of glacier ice has increased significantly over the observed period from the early 1960s to the present. Currently, global glacier mass loss is equivalent to three times the combined ice volume of all glaciers in the European Alps and corresponds to more than 1 mm of sea level rise every year. This melted ice therefore accounts for 25–30% of the currently observed increase in global sea levels. The annual ice loss of all glaciers over the past decade is roughly the same as the mass loss of the Greenland ice sheet, and clearly exceeds that of the Antarctic ice sheet.

*Figure 2. Climate stripes[[3]](#) of annual global glacier mass changes (gigatonnes) from 1976 to 2023. Data source: WGMS. Credit: C3S/ECMWF/WGMS.*  
[DOWNLOAD DATA](https://climate.copernicus.eu/sites/default/files/custom-uploads/ESOTC%202023/DATA/ESOTC_2023_DATA_GLOBE_IN_2023_GLACIERS_FIGURES_1_AND_2.zip)

In the Northern Hemisphere, sea ice reaches its maximum extent at the end of winter, usually in March, and its minimum extent at the end of summer, usually in September. Sea ice around Antarctica follows a similar annual cycle, but shifted by about six months and with a larger amplitude, reaching its maximum extent in September and minimum in February or early March.

The area of the ocean covered by sea ice has been monitored by satellite almost continuously since 1978. Over the past four decades, Arctic sea ice extent has decreased substantially, particularly in September. Between the 1980s and the 2010s, the average sea ice extent in September shrunk by one third, representing a loss of 2.6 million km2, or five times the size of Spain. The thickness of Arctic sea ice is also monitored from space, but this satellite record is much shorter than for sea ice concentration and only available for the winter months[[9]](#), making it more difficult to identify long-term trends. The data do show that, unlike sea ice extent in the Arctic, sea ice extent around Antarctica does not show any clear long-term trend overall as its recent evolution has been dominated by large year-to-year variability. This contrast in sea ice changes between the two polar regions is due to differences in geography and environment.

![arctic sea ice concentration](/sites/default/files/inline-images/fig8b_GCH2023_seaice_concentration_monthly_2023_arctic_animation.gif)

![arctic sea ice concentration](/sites/default/files/inline-images/fig8b_GCH2023_seaice_concentration_monthly_2023_arctic_animation.gif)![Antarctic sea ice concentration](/sites/default/files/inline-images/fig8a_GCH2023_seaice_concentration_monthly_2023_antarctic_animation.gif)

The two polar ice sheets, covering most of Antarctica and Greenland, store most of Earth’s freshwater resources. The Greenland ice sheet covers an area of 1.7 million km2 and stores a volume of 3.0 million km3 of ice[[3]](#), while the Antarctic ice sheet covers an area four times larger (12.3 million km2, excluding the ice shelves) and stores 26.5 million km3 of ice[[4]](#). Combined, the two ice sheets hold enough frozen water that, if it were to melt, it would raise global mean sea level by around 65.3 m.

Estimates derived from satellite measurements[[5]](#) show that between 1992 and 2020, the Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets lost a total of 7.6 trillion tonnes of ice, contributing 21 mm to global mean sea level rise. Ice losses from both the Antarctic and Greenland ice sheets have accelerated during recent decades.

